Automated data download

Author

Brendan Turley

This is a quick tutorial on different ways to download data for use in R. While there are lots of different types of data and different data sources (we could spend multiple sessions talking about just that), this will focus on gridded data easily accessible from NOAA stored in NetCDF format following the Adapt NE SOE Indicator tutorial by downloading OISST anomaly data.

First, some R housekeeping by loading needed libraries. I will be keeping this simple by using minimal packages (sorry tidyverse folks).

Code 
library(cmocean)
library(fields)
library(ncdf4)
library(rerddap)
library(rgdal)

1. Manual download and plotting

The NEFSC Ecodata package pulls the data from NOAAâs Physical Science Laboratory website. You can download the data manually by selecting the download daily SST anomaly link. Then, download the 2023 daily SST anomaly netcdf select âHTTPServerâ to download the file on to you computer and open Netcdf file in R like this:

setwd('~/Downloads')

data <- nc_open('sst.day.anom.2023.nc')

Now, lets pull out the dimensional variables: time, longitude, and latitude.

Code 
time <- ncvar_get(data, 'time')
time <- as.Date(time, origin = '1800-01-01 00:00:00')

lon <- ncvar_get(data, 'lon')
lat <- ncvar_get(data, 'lat')

Then pull the missing data value and SST anomaly data, then assign the missing values and check out the dimensions.

Code 
missing <- ncatt_get(data, 'anom' ,'missing_value')
ssta <- ncvar_get(data, 'anom')

ssta[which(ssta == missing$value)] <- NA

dim(ssta)
[1] 1440  720  101

The order of the dimension are lon, lat and, time. Thatâs global data, but we only want the Gulf of Mexico in this example. Define the region of interest, extract only the important bits, and plot.

Code 
# define GOM
lonbox_e <- -79 + 360
lonbox_w <- -99 + 360
latbox_n <- 31
latbox_s <- 17.5

# indices for GOM lon/lat
ind_lon <- which(lon>=lonbox_w & lon<=lonbox_e)
ind_lat <- which(lat>=latbox_s & lat<=latbox_n)

# only extract GOM
ssta <- ncvar_get(data, 'anom',
                  start = c(ind_lon[1], ind_lat[1], 1),
                  count = c(length(ind_lon), length(ind_lat), length(time)))

ssta[which(ssta == missing$value)] <- NA

image(ssta[ , , 100])

Looks like the Gulf of Mexico. But letâs make a prettier plot.

Code 
### load map
setwd("~/Desktop/professional/biblioteca/data/shapefiles/ne_10m_admin_0_countries")

2. Automated download via THREDDS/OpenDAP

Now lets do this via THREDDS and OpenDAP. You can go to the THREDDS server catalog. Click on the daily SST anomaly for 2023 link, then click the OpenDAP link. Here you can view all the metadata for the file. Find the Data URL field, copy that link, and paste into R. From there you can open the Netcdf file directly in R without manual download and extract everything like we did above with the same code.

3. Automated download via ERDDAP

From NOAA NCEI Climate Data Records there is a link to an ERDDAP server with this dataset. Since weâre interested in 2023, use the Prelimary data. From there, you can generate an API link to download the part you wnat, but someone made a handy ERDDAP R package. Weâre only going to use the package here. From the ERDDAP server all you need is the Dataset ID. Paste that into the RERDDAP info function and specify which ERDDAP server you want:

Code 
ssta_pull <- info('ncdc_oisst_v2_avhrr_prelim_by_time_zlev_lat_lon',
                  url = 'https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/erddap/')
ssta_pull

latitude = c(latbox_s, latbox_n)
longitude = c(lonbox_w, lonbox_e)

ssta_grab <- griddap(ssta_pull,
                     time = c('2023-03-29', '2023-04-10'),
                     latitude = latitude,
                     longitude = longitude,
                     fields = 'anom')

The output format is not convenient to plot as I have been plotting, so I made a function rearrange the output to be more how I like it:

Code 
erddap_extract <- function(data, info, parameter){
  data_temp <- data$data
  ind_extract <- which(names(data_temp)==parameter)
  time_step <- unique(data_temp$time)
  lon <- data$summary$dim$longitude$vals
  lat <- data$summary$dim$latitude$vals
  
  new_data <- array(data_temp[,ind_extract], 
                    c(length(lon),
                      length(lat),
                      length(time_step)))
  
  row_ind <- which(info$alldata$NC_GLOBAL$attribute_name=='title')
  col_ind <- which(colnames(info$alldata$NC_GLOBAL)=='value')
  name <- info$alldata$NC_GLOBAL[row_ind,col_ind]
  name <- unlist(strsplit(name,split=','))
  return(list(data = new_data,
              lon = lon,
              lat = lat,
              time = time_step,
              name = name))
}

Then extract the data, assign NAs to NaN (the plotting function didnât like NaN), and plot like before:

Code 
ssta_m <- erddap_extract(ssta_grab,ssta_pull,'anom')
ssta_m$data[which(ssta_m$data=='NaN')] <- NA

imagePlot(ssta_m$lon - 360,
          ssta_m$lat,
          ssta_m$data[ , , 13],
          asp = 1, las = 1, xlab = 'Longitude', ylab = 'Latitude',
          col = cmocean('balance')(50), breaks = seq(-5,5,.2))
plot(world, add=T, col = 'gray70')
